<DOC><DOCNO> AP880301-0233 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0112EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights TwoTakes   03-01 0507</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0530</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The October stock market crash will contributeto a significant slowdown in economic growth this year but thecountry should be able to avoid a recession, economists for topU.S. corporations say.   The National Association of Business Economists said Monday itslatest member survey found economists were more upbeat than threemonths ago when more than half of them said the record fall instock prices on Oct. 19 would lead to a recession in 1988.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal appeals court has agreed to delay aruling that would have given some banks limited investment bankingpowers.   Monday's ruling provided the securities industry with alast-minute boost in its effort to keep banks off its turf.   The one-page stay by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals inNew York came a day before the scheduled expiration of aseven-month moratorium on new bank powers passed by Congress lastsummer.</TEXT><DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The partnership controlled by T. BoonePickens Jr. has offered to buy Homestake Mining Co., the nation'slargest gold producer, for about $1.9 billion in cash.   In a letter to Homestake Chairman Harry Conger, Mesa LimitedPartnership offered Monday to negotiate an agreement to buy allcommon shares of the San Francisco-based mining company for $20 ashare. Homestake has about 93 million shares outstanding, and didnot immediately respond to the offer.</TEXT><DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two companies controlled bytelevision producer Burt Sugarman have proposed taking overVirginia-based newspaper publisher and broadcaster Media GeneralInc. for $1.75 billion.   But the family of Media General's chairman, D. Tennant Bryan,which controls a majority of the company's voting stock, indicatedMonday it wasn't interested in the proposal from Sugarman, whoseinvestments range from game shows to waste disposal.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stop andamp; Shop Cos. Inc. has agreed to be acquired ina $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by the investment firm KohlbergKravis Roberts Inc.   But hostile suitor Dart Group Corp. said Monday it remainedintent on trying to gain control of the retailer.   Stop andamp; Shop said a Kohlberg Kravis subsidiary, SSC HoldingsCorp., will purchase at least 66 percent of the 28 millionoutstanding Stop andamp; Shop shares at $44 each.   Dart, meanwhile, extended until March 9 an offer of $37 a sharefor all outstanding Stop andamp; Shop stock and indicated it planned togo ahead with a proxy fight to replace Stop andamp; Shop directors laterthis month.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The head of American Express Co. is suggestingcreation of a new international financial organization to help easethe debt crisis of developing nations by buying their loans.   Chairman James D. Robinson III said Monday the organizationwould buy outstanding Third World loans at a discount and thenoffer the banks which had held the loans new, long-term securtiesin exchange.   Robinson said he hoped the proposal will spark a dialoguebecause of the risk of a debt crisis.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>